        Brightbloom bounces higher.

        "Aren't they? And they smell wonderful! Not right now—too early in the day—but at sunset they release fragrance to attract night pollinators, very strategic timing— you'll love it tonight!"

        Streamwalker raises what might have been a vine-hand.

        "River."

        And there it is.

        I stop at the bank, assessing. The river runs maybe twenty meters wide, water moving steadily but not rushing—dark greenish-brown, impossible to see the bottom. Trees lean over from both banks, their canopies almost touching.

        "How deep?" I ask.

        Streamwalker answers with their musical voice, warm and without urgency—

        "Chest height at the crossing point. Current is gentle here. Steady but patient. The water knows where it's going."

        Brightbloom rolls forward—their bouncy movement is really quite Scout-like.

        "It's a lovely crossing! Very safe! We've guided dozens of travelers through—never lost anyone!¶Well, there was that one incident, but they were fine eventually!"

        "Eventually?" I repeat.

        "Downstream in the shallows!" Brightbloom's flowers bloom.

        "Just took a little swim first! Very refreshing, they said!"

        Streamwalker makes a sound like a gentle sigh—air through their hollow vine chambers.

        "We will walk together. The stones are stable. No swimming required."

        I study the water. In Territory One, I'd have been anxious—new challenge, unknown depth, worried about currents—but three days of learning to trust Leafwhisper and Rootwalker taught me something: the guides know what they're doing.

        "Okay," I say. "Show me how."

        Streamwalker moves to the water's edge. Their vines extend, testing the surface, then slide in with barely a ripple.

        "Step where I step. The river has a path—stones beneath the surface, placed by the network generations ago. Trust the current to guide you if you slip. It flows to safety."

        Streamwalker steps into the water. Their vines spread wide for balance, moving with the current instead of fighting it—graceful, flowing. The water seems to accept them, wrapping around their structure like an embrace.

        "See how calm they are?" Brightbloom says, bouncing at the bank beside me. "Streamwalker practically _is_ water! So relaxing to watch! You're going to do great—I can tell, you have excellent balance from watching you walk—"

        "I'm ready," I say. And I surprise myself by meaning it.

        Scout bounces once, then launches themselves into the river with complete confidence. They bob on the surface, delighted, and float-bounce along behind Streamwalker.

        Right. If a ball-shaped plant can do this, I can too.

        I step into the water.

        Cold—immediate and shocking. My boot finds stone, solid beneath the silt, just like Streamwalker said.

        "There you go!" Brightbloom calls. "Perfect! Next step just ahead and slightly right—yes! Excellent!"

        The water rises to my knees, then to my thighs, the current pushing gently against my legs—not threatening, just present, letting me know it exists.
      </text>
