        Brightbloom bounces toward a cluster of bright yellow flowers and says,
        "Plus you'll be warm from movement! — Walking generates heat — very efficient biological response — and look — these bloom in afternoon sun, very beautiful, excellent motivational scenery for the next few kilometers!"

        I squeeze water from my jacket; my pants will take longer to dry, but Streamwalker is right — walking will warm me up. The sun feels good already, stronger here without the forest canopy blocking it.

        I ask, "How far to tonight's shelter?"

        Streamwalker replies, "Three hours — gentle walking. No more crossings today. The path flows easy from here."

        I say, "Easy is good. I like easy."

        Brightbloom bounces, enthusiastic and bright, and says,
        "Easy is wonderful! — Though challenging is also good! — Builds confidence! — Creates accomplishment! — But easy is definitely lovely too!"

        Scout bounces between me and Brightbloom, apparently having adopted the bush as a bouncing mentor.

        We continue walking through the wetlands — water and sky and colorful plants, everything bright and alive and completely different from Territory One's shadowed forest. The ground stays soft, sometimes splashing underfoot, sometimes just yielding like moss.

        Streamwalker leads with flowing grace, moving like they're part of the water themselves.

        Brightbloom bounces and chatters, pointing out interesting plants and encouraging me every few minutes about my "excellent walking form."

        Scout investigates everything with enthusiastic thoroughness.

        And I — adapt.

        ¶

        I've done this before — learned new guides, new terrain, new rhythms. This time feels easier. Less fear about the unknown, more curiosity about the differences. Streamwalker isn't Rootwalker and Brightbloom definitely isn't Leafwhisper — but that is okay. Calm and energy instead of information and practicality — different but functional.

        By the time we reach the evening shelter — a raised platform of woven reeds surrounded by flowering bushes — my clothes have mostly dried and my muscles have found their rhythm again.

        Streamwalker settles at the platform's edge, vines trailing into the water below, and says,
        "Good walking today. The river blessed your crossing."

        I ask, "Blessed?" while pulling out my food supplies.

        Streamwalker's musical voice carries gentle amusement as they say, "Old saying — water that lets you pass without taking you. That's a blessing."

        Brightbloom bounces onto the platform, flowers glowing in the evening light, and says,
        "*You were wonderful!* — First day with new guides and you adapted so well — such confidence — very impressive!"

        Scout bounces agreement and settles beside me.

        I eat my mushroom paste — still terrible but necessary — and watch the sun set over the wetlands: purple and orange sky reflecting in standing water, flowers starting to release fragrance like Brightbloom predicted. It is beautiful, different from Territory One's forest darkness but beautiful in its own way.
      </text>
